Creating images with R

with a little bit of magick

Jenny Xinyue Zhang

2023-03-09

✨My meme ✨

This meme is about how we always got bugs when coding, and I find it quite funny.

an original meme created by me

library(magick)

frame_bottom <- image_read("https://hips.hearstapps.com/hmg-prod/images/womanyellingcat-1573233850.jpg?resize=1200:*")%>%
  image_scale("400")
#by scaling the original image down to 400px 
#means that I can create two blanks with the width of 200px
#and append them together would give me 400px

frame_top_left <- image_blank(width = "200",
                              height = "100",
                              color = "#f0f0ed")%>%
  image_annotate(text = "There were 13 bugs  
and I just fixed 1,  
TELL ME AGAIN
how many are there now?", 
                 font = "Impact",
                 size = 17, 
                 gravity = "center", 
                 color = "black")

frame_top_right <- image_blank(width = "200",
                               height = "100",
                               color = "#f0f0ed")%>%
  image_annotate(text = "21.", 
                 font = "Impact",
                 size = 30, 
                 gravity = "center", 
                 color = "black")
#since there are a lot more text on the right hand side
#and not much on the left, i used different text size
#on each side

frame_top <- c(frame_top_left, frame_top_right) %>%
  image_append()

whole_meme <- c(frame_top, frame_bottom)%>%
  image_append(stack = TRUE)

image_write(whole_meme, "my_meme.png")

✨My animated GIF ✨

I create a good morning and greeting GIF that could be used as a phone wallpaper, and I used my favorite colors on it.

an original animated GIF created by me

library(magick)

background <- image_read("https://img.freepik.com/free-photo/grunge-paint-background_1409-1337.jpg")%>%
  image_scale("400")%>%
  image_rotate(270)
#I want to make vertical gif so I found this rotate function and 
#rotate the background by 270 degrees.


frame_1 <- image_annotate(background,
                          text = "  
                            
Hi",
                          font = "Impact",
                          size = 30,
                          color = "#dcdcfc",
                          location = "+100-10")

frame_2 <- image_annotate(frame_1 ,
                          text = "Good morning",
                          font = "Impact",
                          size = 30,
                          color = "#b0b0ff",
                          location = "+35+140")

frame_3 <- image_annotate(frame_2, 
                          text = "How are you?",
                      font = "Impact",
                      size = 30,
                      color = "#8f8fff",
                      location = "+40+220")

frame_4 <- image_annotate(frame_3, 
                          text = "Have a good day!",
                          font = "Impact",
                          size = 30,
                          color = "#6868fc",
                          location = "+20+300")
#I found this location numbers quite confusing but i just keep trying numbers 
#until I got the result I want. 

frames <- c(frame_1, frame_2, frame_3, frame_4)

animation <- image_morph(frames) %>%
  image_animate(fps = 5)
#I also used morph function to change smoothly between images. 

image_write(animation, "animation.gif")
